    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="MTA27">
<l>malaiyāṟ kuṭaikavittu māvāy piḷantu</l>
<l>cilaiyāṉ marāmaramēḻ ceṟṟuk – kolaiyāṉaip</l>
<l>pōrkkō ṭocittaṉavum pūṅkuruntañ cāyttaṉavuṅ</l>
<l>kārkkōṭu paṟṟiyāṉ kai</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>Covering [the world] with a mountain as umbrella, tearing open the mouth of the horse<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">This is the first of numerous references to Kṛṣṇa overcoming the horse demon kēśin; cf. Pū. 28.4, 93.3 Pē. 42.2, 47.3, 48.3, 98.4.</note>,</l>
<l>destroying with the bow seven Cadamba trees<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">This is a reference to Rāma’s piercing with one arrow and destroying the seven Cadamba trees in order to prove to Sugrīva his prowess as a warrior; cf. Pē. 52.1.</note> – the hands</l>
<l>of him who seized the clouded peak are those that broke the battle tusk</l>
<l>of the murderous elephant and that bent the flowering wild lime tree.<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">For the bending of the wild lime tree (kuruntu; here and Poykai 54.1+3, 62.1 Pē. 32.4), cf. Cilappatikāram 17.21 – possibly a variation on the frequent motif of passing in between the myrobalam trees (marutu).</note></l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
